text.__SUMMARY__: Common names: dark-spotted anaconda, De Schauensee's anaconda.Eunectes deschauenseei is a non-venomous boa species endemic to northeastern South America. No subspecies are currently recognized.
text.Taxonomy: The specific name, deschauenseei, is in honor of American ornithologist  Rodolphe Meyer de Schauensee, who donated a specimen to the Philadelphia Zoo in 1924. The type locality given is "probably collected on the island of Marajo at the mouth of the Amazon".
text.Distribution and habitat: E. deschauenseei is found in South America, in northeastern Brazil (Pará and Amapá states) and French Guiana. E. deschauenseei is a semi-aquatic species usually found in swampy, seasonally flooded freshwater areas at elevations below 300 m (980 ft).
text.Description: Adult males measure 130–211 cm (51–83 in) and adult females 120–231 cm (47–91 in) in snout–vent length.
text.Reproduction: Vitellogenesis in E. deschauenseei probably occurs from autumn to spring (May to December). Gestation may last as long as nine months. Litter size among five gravid females ranged from 3 to 27 (mean 10.6). Newborns measure 29–53 cm (11–21 in) in snout–vent length.
text.Conservation: The savanna habitat of E. deschauenseei is highly threatened by agricultural expansion, but the threat posed on this species is not known.
